    "## 6. Mechanism summary — why each method behaves the way it does\n",
    "\n",
    "| method            | scales fit?     | behaviour                                               | failure mode                                       |\n",
    "|-------------------|-----------------|---------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------------|\n",
    "| **M3-ICP-locked** | locked          | Only SE(3) refinement on top of the GT-validated pin    | Diverges if warmstart > convergence radius (NN basin too wide) |\n",
    "| **C5**            | re-fit per member, ensembled | Density-priority dispatch picks the best of P1/P4/P6 | Smaller drift than P3 (members vary), but each member can re-fit sxy/sz away from the pin |\n",
    "| **P3 RANSAC**     | re-fit per RANSAC sample + final inlier refit | 4-correspondence aniso-affine has too many DOF for the noise level | Recovered sz drifts ≥ 5–30 % from GT pin → systematic z-error across all pairs |\n",
    "| **P5 FGW** (dropped) | re-fit, distance-based | Optimal-transport on point clouds | Solver collapses regardless of warmstart |\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why P3 RANSAC fails while ICP succeeds (the user's specific question).**\n",
    "\n",
    "P3 and M3-ICP both consume the *same* corrected warmstart (LP + sz pin).  They differ in *what they fit on top*:\n",
    "\n",
    "* P3 fits **all 7 DOF** of an anisotropic affine on every 4-tuple sample.  This is the same problem that motivated v2 in the first place (v1 §11: P3 \"7-DOF under-determined\").  Locking the prior moves the *initial cloud* into the right region, but P3 still re-derives sxy and sz from 4 noisy NN correspondences.  With a 5 µm per-point noise and ~150 µm depth span across 4 points, the aniso-affine fit's sz-uncertainty is on the order of 5/150 ≈ 3.3 % per sample; refitting on the inlier set sometimes converges to within 5 %, sometimes drifts to 20–30 %.  Empirically (see Section 4 table) it lands 5–15 % off on most subjects, which is enough to push median pair-error past 20 µm.\n",
    "* M3-ICP-locked fits **only 6 DOF** (rotation + translation), with scales fixed at the GT-validated values.  The pinned scales (sz error ≈ 0.040 µm / 1.4 % vs GT) are *more accurate than what RANSAC could recover from 4 NN matches*.  Since ICP can only correct (R, t), it has no degree of freedom to re-introduce a scale error.  The convergence basin is much wider in this restricted parameter space (the gradient in scale space is effectively zero).\n",
    "\n",
    "**One-sentence summary.**  v2-S02 iter-7 image-NCC gives us scales accurate to ~1 %; M3-ICP locks them in and refines only the small remaining (R, t); P3 throws them away and rederives them from 4 noisy point correspondences. So when the prior is right, fitting fewer DOF wins.\n",
    "\n",
    "**One-sentence summary of the 2/6 ICP failures.**  Locking the right scales is necessary but not sufficient — ICP also requires the warmstart to land within ~25 µm of truth in xy/z; on 755252 and 782149 it doesn't, and ICP either stalls (755252) or diverges (782149).  The Δd_med gate catches both cases reliably."
